{"author":{"id":"8e1777f58c0cfe5478428be8f9fcbfe90d25e44689578335da8fc2246fe0915a"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1630773436,"nonce":"xQaQD8+CVr2zL9J0auO+1vv24oY=","metadata":{"github-id":"MDU6SXNzdWU5ODgzMjcwODg=","github-url":"https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/issues/3921","origin":"github"},"title":"How do we handle (insecure) RData objects as input to tools","message":"Hi IUC.\nCould you please have a look at https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/pull/3859\n\nIt's the old discussion about the security of RData objects. Do we allow in IUC tools RData as input datasets. This implies in the worst case that some hand-crafted RData object can be uploaded into Galaxy and could do some (no clue which) harm.\n\nrelated: https://github.com/galaxyproject/galaxy/pull/12336\nxref: https://github.com/usegalaxy-eu/usegalaxy-eu-tools/pull/411#issuecomment-912474989\n\nSide note, we have the same problem with Python objects, for example in with Machine Learning models. We put a lot of effort into allow-listing functions and objects and skip others to make it secure.\n\nWe few thoughts from my side.\n- I think in an ideal world it would be nice if we can avoid RData objects, but realistically this raises the bar for tools to enter the usegalaxy.* servers significantly.\n- we can say IUC does not allow this and recommend using some other converters (in this example some Loom converters), but this is not always possible\n- even if IUC does not allow this, we will have highly used tools that will make use of that and entire communities --\u003e metabolomics for example\n- we could add a new tag into the tool, e.g. `\u003ctool .... potentially_insecure_data_handling=\"true\"\u003e` which forces Galaxy (if configured) to use containers\n  - no clue how this would work with destination configurations\n  - no clue if this would be secure enough, but at least we could indicate this to the Galaxy admin in a structured way","files":null}]}